<BaseLayout title="keepitmovin vs. copying context" description="Compare live coding-agent handoffs with manual copy and paste.">
  <article class="docs-content prose standalone-prose container">
    <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p><h1>keepitmovin vs. copying context</h1>
    <p>Copy and paste is free, universal, and often enough for a short task. Its weakness is timing: the useful state is easiest to forget precisely when a limit or crash interrupts you.</p>
    <h2>What keepitmovin adds</h2>
    <p>The working agent maintains a local handoff with the goal, decisions, changed files, checks, blockers, and next action. The next tool receives that file automatically.</p>
    <h2>When copying is better</h2>
    <p>Use manual context for a one-off question, a short task, or when you do not want another local artifact. Use keepitmovin when the task spans tools or long sessions.</p>
    <p><a href="/docs/handoff">See exactly what the handoff contains →</a></p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
